WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.429 --> 00:00:01.970
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:01.970 --> 00:00:03.650
It's good to have you here.

00:00:03.650 --> 00:00:07.370
I see some familiar faces
and some less familiar faces.

00:00:07.370 --> 00:00:09.520
So that's fantastic.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:14.570
So what I wanted to
do is prepare to talk.

00:00:14.570 --> 00:00:18.195
And within the talk,
I have some images,

00:00:18.195 --> 00:00:21.380
a few videos to look
at, and there's also

00:00:21.380 --> 00:00:24.110
a audience
participation component,

00:00:24.110 --> 00:00:26.000
because that's just how I roll.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.030
We have to practice
what we're up to.

00:00:29.030 --> 00:00:37.410
So this segment, this talk, is
one that is looking at pedagogy

00:00:37.410 --> 00:00:42.060
as not simply pedagogical
strategies in general

00:00:42.060 --> 00:00:44.520
but to look more at the
ways that I translate

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:48.840
this idea of pedagogy through
lenses or filters of disruption

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:50.730
or of criticality.

00:00:50.730 --> 00:00:56.370
And so part of the work
that I do professionally

00:00:56.370 --> 00:01:00.050
is prepare teachers
of art for K12.

00:01:00.050 --> 00:01:03.420
But I also work with
graduate students

00:01:03.420 --> 00:01:05.670
as they conduct their
research, I also

00:01:05.670 --> 00:01:09.690
do my own research
in scholarly kinds

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:14.280
of moves about the ways in which
visual imagery, visual art,

00:01:14.280 --> 00:01:20.250
visual cultural production,
functions, as modes or spaces

00:01:20.250 --> 00:01:22.170
for teaching and learning.

00:01:22.170 --> 00:01:25.890
Jasper Johns, a
pop artist, someone

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.420
who's been relegated
into that space

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:29.724
by some critics and
historians, this

00:01:29.724 --> 00:01:31.140
is something--
this is a statement

00:01:31.140 --> 00:01:33.089
he made about his art practice.

00:01:33.089 --> 00:01:34.380
Like, how do you make your art?

00:01:34.380 --> 00:01:35.940
What's your approach?

00:01:35.940 --> 00:01:38.580
Take an objective,
do something to it,

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:40.420
and I do something else to it.

00:01:40.420 --> 00:01:41.330
Really?

00:01:41.330 --> 00:01:43.920
Well, yeah, I mean, that
seems really simplified.

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:49.170
But for me, that's a really
interesting and quite powerful

00:01:49.170 --> 00:01:51.770
methodology or method to use.

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:55.410
You take something, and then
that thing is not just--

00:01:55.410 --> 00:01:56.972
it's not finished.

00:01:56.972 --> 00:01:58.680
It's not done being
whatever it could be.

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:00.710
And then, do something to it.

00:02:00.710 --> 00:02:03.190
OK, but then, keep it going.

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:04.210
Do something else do it.

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:06.870
So for me, the doing can
happen in a number of ways.

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:09.120
You can alter it, you can
modify it, you can throw it.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:10.139
You can add something to it.

00:02:10.139 --> 00:02:11.430
You can take something away.

00:02:11.430 --> 00:02:15.030
But we can also, as
viewers or people

00:02:15.030 --> 00:02:17.610
who are engaging with that
object, we might ask questions.

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:20.610
So the asking questions
is a form of doing.

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:24.480
And so for me, Johns's
quotation is nice, for me,

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:27.600
as a bridge from a more
modernist mindset or approach

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:29.100
where it's about
the object and it's

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:31.759
about the making, the
process of making to--

00:02:31.759 --> 00:02:33.300
some books might
talk about the slide

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.630
into postmodernism
or other post spaces,

00:02:36.630 --> 00:02:41.110
where we move beyond
objectness or materialness

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:46.760
to other realms that have
more conceptual content

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:48.180
and interest.

00:02:48.180 --> 00:02:50.460
That notion of asking
questions or take an object,

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:52.543
doing something to it,
doing something else to it,

00:02:52.543 --> 00:02:54.780
you could engage
learners like that.

00:02:54.780 --> 00:02:57.576
That's one way to
engage learners.

00:02:57.576 --> 00:02:58.950
So if we think
about learners, we

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:00.420
should also think
about curriculum.

00:03:00.420 --> 00:03:01.960
Now, this is an image--

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:03.930
this is not one that
I drew, but it's

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:09.990
a cartoon, a single cartoon
panel from Non Sequitur.

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:13.640
And I use this image when
I teach curriculum classes.

00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:16.447
So on the right, we
have this larger fish

00:03:16.447 --> 00:03:18.780
with kind of sharp teeth, and
there's stuff falling down

00:03:18.780 --> 00:03:22.020
from the fish's mouth, and then
there are these three smaller

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:24.987
fish, and then there's
another fish that's

00:03:24.987 --> 00:03:27.570
kind of medium sized, and that
one actually knows how to talk,

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:29.580
which I think is an
interesting thing.

00:03:29.580 --> 00:03:32.960
So we're able to
know what fish say.

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:37.360
The medium-sized fish says,
"No, we can't swim any faster.

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:40.440
The school curriculum is
geared for the slower swimmers.

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:44.650
So the 10 of you have to wait
for the others to catch up."

00:03:44.650 --> 00:03:47.860
I don't know about you, I
only see four other fish.

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:49.050
I only see four other fish.

00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:50.520
I do see one fish.

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:52.770
It looks like little fish
bits that are falling

00:03:52.770 --> 00:03:55.530
from this larger fish's mouth.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:58.690
So where is the curriculum?

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:00.580
Here, is the curriculum
this larger fish

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:02.530
with the sharp teeth?

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:06.520
Is the curriculum the swimming?

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:08.230
Is the curriculum
the water itself?

00:04:08.230 --> 00:04:11.530
This cartoon allows us to have
multiple entry points to ask

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:13.720
where the curriculum resides.

00:04:13.720 --> 00:04:18.880
And if we think about
that word "curriculum,"

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:24.590
it is derived from a Latin
word, currere. and that's

00:04:24.590 --> 00:04:29.720
the infinitive "to run" So
"curriculum" is "to run."

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:33.620
It's the running of a
course, rather than a noun.

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:36.500
We think about it in
those terms, right?

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:42.052
Curriculum theorists did
work in the '70s and '80s

00:04:42.052 --> 00:04:43.760
to reconceptualize
curriculum, but didn't

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:48.390
focus on this idea of
curriculum as a verb "to run."

00:04:48.390 --> 00:04:52.240
So the running or, in this
case, the swimming of the course

00:04:52.240 --> 00:04:55.210
is the curriculum--
so how they swim.

00:04:55.210 --> 00:04:59.800
I'm assuming the medium-sized
fish is the teacher

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:04.030
and could be, could also
be the school principal

00:05:04.030 --> 00:05:06.250
or whoever is in charge there.

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:08.830
But the middle
three are probably--

00:05:08.830 --> 00:05:12.370
or this is supposed to
be maybe the students who

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:14.680
seem to know how to
swim the course the way

00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:16.970
that it was designed.

00:05:16.970 --> 00:05:19.150
Well, this could be
one of the learners,

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:20.800
too, swimming adequately.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:25.260
But sometimes when I have used
this image with my students

00:05:25.260 --> 00:05:28.000
in curriculum courses, they
talk about how this larger fish,

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:29.846
they often call
it the barracuda--

00:05:29.846 --> 00:05:30.970
see, that's the curriculum.

00:05:30.970 --> 00:05:33.370
The curriculum eats
up the swimmers

00:05:33.370 --> 00:05:37.040
who don't swim in
predetermined ways.

00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:40.780
Oh, OK, so here, a
curriculum is a noun

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:42.580
and an adversarial thing.

00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:45.160
How depressing is that to
be a teacher or a learner

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.940
to think the curriculum's
after you; you better stay

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:49.115
in front of it?

00:05:49.115 --> 00:05:50.490
But if we think
of the curriculum

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:52.860
as a verb in the ways
in which we swim,

00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.250
maybe some swimmers swim higher
in the water, some swim lower,

00:05:56.250 --> 00:06:00.360
some swim sideways, some
swim faster and slower.

00:06:00.360 --> 00:06:02.910
How might the curriculum
allow for multiple swimmers

00:06:02.910 --> 00:06:05.490
rather than a predetermined
and singular notion

00:06:05.490 --> 00:06:07.890
of what a learner could be.

00:06:07.890 --> 00:06:12.845
But that's if we privilege
the idea of learning.

00:06:12.845 --> 00:06:15.150
If we think about teaching,
we can just deliver.

00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:20.400
I mean, there are notions
of teaching and curriculum

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:25.710
that, from the early 1900s and
late 1800s that would proclaim

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:29.534
that learners are empty
vessels, and the teacher

00:06:29.534 --> 00:06:30.450
has all the knowledge.

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:32.790
We just fill you
up with knowledge.

00:06:32.790 --> 00:06:34.560
And that says, well,
you're a learner.

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:36.330
You don't bring anything
to the classroom.

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:37.330
But that's not the case.

00:06:37.330 --> 00:06:39.000
You swim the way you swim.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.360
Bring that to the classroom.

00:06:40.360 --> 00:06:43.500
So this idea of shifting from
teaching to learning privileges

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:48.540
or allows more attention to what
learners bring to those spaces.

00:06:48.540 --> 00:06:50.820
Well, another
standardized approach

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:54.600
that was very popular
100 years ago and still

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:59.160
somehow is popular within
some circles in art teaching

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.410
and education are
the elements of art

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:03.687
and the principles of design.

00:07:03.687 --> 00:07:05.770
Some people call them the
elements and principles.

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:08.500
But it's the elements of art
and principles of design.

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:10.760
And certainly, these
are ways to say, look,

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:13.720
these are the things that are
going on in visual imagery

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:16.780
or material culture.

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:19.690
But they weren't intended
to be the limitations.

00:07:19.690 --> 00:07:22.000
They were intended to be
ways to gain access to what

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:23.470
we're seeing in front of us.

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:27.340
Misinterpretation of
that, quite often,

00:07:27.340 --> 00:07:29.679
studio teachers, art
teachers, other folks

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:31.220
will think that
these are the limits.

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:33.844
And if we only talk about line,
shape, color, texture, pattern,

00:07:33.844 --> 00:07:38.532
rhythm, then we've
covered the curriculum.

00:07:38.532 --> 00:07:39.990
We've taught what
we need to teach.

00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:41.910
Well, that's an
interesting approach

00:07:41.910 --> 00:07:45.540
if you want to avoid
content, if you

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:47.790
want to avoid
concepts, and ideas,

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:51.600
and social issues--
if you want to avoid

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:55.411
lived experiences in the
lives of other people.

00:07:55.411 --> 00:07:57.660
And certainly when you're
looking at works of art that

00:07:57.660 --> 00:08:01.320
are representative or
reflections of lived

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:06.450
experiences to omit interest in
what we're seeing and what is

00:08:06.450 --> 00:08:10.110
being represented by simply
limiting it to a formalist--

00:08:10.110 --> 00:08:12.750
and this is formalized notions--

00:08:12.750 --> 00:08:15.720
then, we're missing part
of the conversation.

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:19.200
So a number of years
ago, Olivia Gude,

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:24.360
who is a scholar at School of
the Art Institute in Chicago.

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:27.270
She said, look, we're not
in this modernist notion,

00:08:27.270 --> 00:08:28.770
and there are
different ways that we

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:32.250
can mobilize art practices.

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:35.850
And she constructed this
set of postmodern principles

00:08:35.850 --> 00:08:37.919
by looking at the work
that her students were

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:44.159
making during weekend art
classes in the Spiral Workshop.

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:47.250
And she said, you know,
there's other principles,

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:49.650
the elements of art and
principles of design,

00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:51.270
those seven--

00:08:51.270 --> 00:08:54.910
group of seven elements and
group of seven principles

00:08:54.910 --> 00:09:00.970
were guiding and have done
some work in art curriculum.

00:09:00.970 --> 00:09:03.760
But she said, as I look at the
work my students are making

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:06.730
based on the
assignments that we're

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:10.990
up to in the Spiral curriculum,
that are focused on themes,

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:14.260
focused on social issues,
focused on concepts,

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:19.330
focused on lived experiences,
she said of all of these works,

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:21.862
these seven principles
seem to emerge,

00:09:21.862 --> 00:09:24.070
not that the elements of
art and principles of design

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:24.611
aren't there.

00:09:24.611 --> 00:09:28.600
Because I kind of dare you to
point to something in the world

00:09:28.600 --> 00:09:31.530
that you can't talk
about in terms of line,

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:35.080
or shape, or texture, right?

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.240
So she's saying
that from looking

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:40.210
at the students' work generated
from a thematic approach

00:09:40.210 --> 00:09:43.480
about concepts and lived
experiences in the world--

00:09:43.480 --> 00:09:46.060
text and image is a
postmodern principle.

00:09:46.060 --> 00:09:51.070
Hybridity, this idea of things
kind of overlapping and merging

00:09:51.070 --> 00:09:53.202
together, gazing, the
way in which one looks,

00:09:53.202 --> 00:09:54.910
and the perspective
from which one looks,

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:57.070
and how one is looked at.

00:09:57.070 --> 00:09:59.770
Representing-- not just
to represent something

00:09:59.770 --> 00:10:02.560
but how one's identity
gets represented

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:04.870
or how one represents oneself.

00:10:04.870 --> 00:10:07.150
Appropriation-- borrowing
from one context or another;

00:10:07.150 --> 00:10:09.130
juxtaposition, the
critique of two objects

00:10:09.130 --> 00:10:11.840
or two images in
relationship to each other.

00:10:11.840 --> 00:10:14.320
Recontextualization,
similar to appropriation,

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:16.060
but taking something
out of one context,

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:17.740
putting it in a
new context, now it

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:19.720
speaks differently about
this other context.

00:10:19.720 --> 00:10:24.970
And layering, this idea of
how narratives or layers can

00:10:24.970 --> 00:10:28.320
be read through each other
for multiple meanings.

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:29.950
And I love what she
says, which is also

00:10:29.950 --> 00:10:32.350
the pull-out quotation
from this article,

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:36.370
"An infinite amount of time is
wasted in misdirected effort

00:10:36.370 --> 00:10:38.770
because tradition
has a strong hold."

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:41.200
I mean, there are other
things that we can be doing,

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:43.780
but, because we're
regimented in tradition,

00:10:43.780 --> 00:10:46.790
we just can't get there.

00:10:46.790 --> 00:10:50.130
All right, so let's engage
some learners like this.

00:10:50.130 --> 00:10:52.500
How about being some learners?

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:53.220
Good?

00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:54.450
All right, I have--

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:56.020
we have large paper.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:59.910
These are essentially
jumbo-sized Post-it notes.

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:01.140
And we have markers.

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.900
We have markers of
different colors.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:06.390
Most of them are
also gigantic sizes.

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:09.120
It's like this larger cartoon
version of Post-it notes

00:11:09.120 --> 00:11:10.560
and little markers.

00:11:10.560 --> 00:11:12.840
And what I would
like you to do is,

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:17.460
we're going to use this approach
where we're going to do--

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:20.280
it's derived from
think, pair, share--

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.800
this approach of
learning, where I

00:11:22.800 --> 00:11:24.810
want you to think on
your own, and then you're

00:11:24.810 --> 00:11:28.364
going to find someone else to
pair with, and connect with,

00:11:28.364 --> 00:11:30.780
and then you're going to share
your ideas with each other,

00:11:30.780 --> 00:11:32.340
then we'll share with the group.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:34.680
So what I'd like
you to do right now

00:11:34.680 --> 00:11:37.420
is, if you have something to
write with, that's great--

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:41.010
I don't think we brought
any normal-sized paper,

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:46.205
but I'll give you two
minutes to do this first part

00:11:46.205 --> 00:11:47.080
to think on your own.

00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:48.974
What I would like you
to do is choose one--

00:11:48.974 --> 00:11:50.640
I'm not going to
decide for you, but I'd

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:56.540
like you to choose on your
own, one of these tasks,

00:11:56.540 --> 00:11:58.040
one of these
statements, and I want

00:11:58.040 --> 00:12:01.517
you to come up with a list.

00:12:01.517 --> 00:12:03.100
So if you choose the
first one, you're

00:12:03.100 --> 00:12:05.260
going to come up with a
list of 10 important women

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:07.060
in the history of the world.

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:08.820
Don't show anybody.

00:12:08.820 --> 00:12:11.820
Keep it to yourself for now.

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.520
Or you could choose
the second one.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:15.270
You can make a list
of 10 important events

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:16.830
in the history of the world.

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:19.590
Or you can make a list of
10 important human creations

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:20.775
in the history of the world.

00:12:20.775 --> 00:12:22.260
Does that make sense?

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:26.040
Two minutes, go for it, and
then we'll come back together.

00:12:26.040 --> 00:12:29.250
The activity that
we are doing is one

00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:32.370
that I use in a curriculum
development class and also

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:34.950
curriculum theory class,
usually near the beginning

00:12:34.950 --> 00:12:38.760
of the semester to underscore
this idea that curriculum

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:41.490
development, curriculum
design, curriculum,

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.110
as a general practice,
is a political act,

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:45.270
and it's based in values.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:48.210
It's based in experiences.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:50.760
Imagine a textbook company
approached you and says,

00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:56.010
oh, you could get this contract
for a textbook, a history book.

00:12:56.010 --> 00:12:59.980
We only have enough
money for 10 chapters.

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:03.660
So if you had 10 weeks to
teach a course, what 10 topics

00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:04.860
would you teach?

00:13:04.860 --> 00:13:07.260
You've got to decide
what doesn't get taught.

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:09.052
Deciding what is not
in the curriculum

00:13:09.052 --> 00:13:10.260
is part of the political act.

00:13:10.260 --> 00:13:12.690
It's part of the
decision-making.

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:15.120
So these three prompts
are ones that I've

00:13:15.120 --> 00:13:17.010
used for years, and
years, and years

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:18.240
to do exactly what we did.

00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:20.510
You did it in like 15 minutes.

00:13:20.510 --> 00:13:23.070
I typically spend 15 minutes
having the students generate

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:24.780
the ideas, then we
spend 45 minutes

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:26.494
critiquing and interpreting.

00:13:26.494 --> 00:13:28.410
We're not going to spend
45 minutes critiquing

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:30.300
and interpreting, but I'll lead
you through some of the things

00:13:30.300 --> 00:13:31.440
that I like to do.

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:34.029
Which prompt was this one?

00:13:34.029 --> 00:13:35.480
AUDIENCE: It's events?

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:37.280
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
This is events?

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:38.135
This one?

00:13:38.135 --> 00:13:39.065
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:13:39.065 --> 00:13:40.070
AUDIENCE: Creations.

00:13:40.070 --> 00:13:41.090
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Creations?

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:41.690
What was this one?

00:13:41.690 --> 00:13:42.170
AUDIENCE: Creations.

00:13:42.170 --> 00:13:43.378
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Creations.

00:13:43.378 --> 00:13:44.170
AUDIENCE: Women.

00:13:44.170 --> 00:13:45.050
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Women.

00:13:45.050 --> 00:13:45.883
AUDIENCE: Creations.

00:13:45.883 --> 00:13:48.190
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Creations.

00:13:48.190 --> 00:13:49.860
Now, notice the
prompts are-- we'll

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:52.380
talk about how I worded the
prompts in a little bit.

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:56.550
I find it interesting-- this
is just the way I'm reading

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:57.630
your lists--

00:13:57.630 --> 00:14:03.960
one, two, three, four of
the five lists use numbers.

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:08.700
My assumption is that the one
entry next to the number one

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:12.660
is the most important,
only because it's listed--

00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:15.240
I'm just kind of culturally--

00:14:15.240 --> 00:14:17.910
you know in that habit.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:20.340
When I see a one, I think
of that being first.

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:23.430
Usually, first is most important
unless you're David Letterman;

00:14:23.430 --> 00:14:25.770
you're reading your
top-10 lists backwards.

00:14:25.770 --> 00:14:30.680
If you had a last-minute email
from the publisher, [GASP]

00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:33.150
we just got some more money.

00:14:33.150 --> 00:14:37.140
We could add another
chapter to your textbook.

00:14:37.140 --> 00:14:40.860
But you've got to tell us by the
end of the business day today.

00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:44.190
Could you come up
with your number 11?

00:14:44.190 --> 00:14:46.140
Right?

00:14:46.140 --> 00:14:47.200
Or, oh, I'm sorry.

00:14:47.200 --> 00:14:49.870
Our budget has been slashed.

00:14:49.870 --> 00:14:52.410
We have to cut two chapters.

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:54.240
Which two are the
least important.

00:14:56.860 --> 00:14:59.260
These are questions that
curriculum designers,

00:14:59.260 --> 00:15:01.900
curriculum developers
make all the time.

00:15:01.900 --> 00:15:03.370
Teachers, how much
time do we have

00:15:03.370 --> 00:15:05.203
in the semester or the
school year to teach?

00:15:05.203 --> 00:15:06.190
Oh, we only got so far.

00:15:06.190 --> 00:15:08.640
We've got to hurry up and rush
because this is more important.

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:10.515
And somebody else told
us this was important,

00:15:10.515 --> 00:15:11.924
so we've got to teach--

00:15:11.924 --> 00:15:13.090
well, I'm not teaching that.

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:15.100
That seems less important.

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:17.090
These are political decisions.

00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:23.680
But what is in is only there
because it wasn't left out.

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:25.780
A critical pedagogy
or pedagogy that I

00:15:25.780 --> 00:15:29.350
like to enact and encourage
my students to use

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:31.120
is one that asks these
kinds of questions.

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:32.887
It's constantly in
this frame of asking.

00:15:32.887 --> 00:15:35.470
Even when we have our list, even
when we have our decision of,

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:37.227
what seems to be important--

00:15:40.209 --> 00:15:43.250
well, why is this on the list?

00:15:43.250 --> 00:15:45.080
And where else does
this allow us to go?

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:51.280
If we take Toni Morrison,
what can we do with her work?

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:53.860
Where does her work allow us
to go, following Jasper Johns?

00:15:53.860 --> 00:15:55.780
And then, where does
that allow us to go?

00:15:55.780 --> 00:15:58.370
Take Toni Morrison,
not an object--

00:15:58.370 --> 00:16:00.630
but we can think
it in those ways--

00:16:00.630 --> 00:16:05.740
take this entry, do something
to it, do something else to it.

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:08.860
The word "most" doesn't appear
in any of those prompts.

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:11.249
Did you pick up on that?

00:16:11.249 --> 00:16:13.540
Why do you think I didn't
put the word "most" in there?

00:16:13.540 --> 00:16:15.100
AUDIENCE: Too much pressure.

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.210
STEPHEN CARPENTER:
Too much pressure?

00:16:17.210 --> 00:16:17.710
On me?

00:16:17.710 --> 00:16:19.317
I could've easily written--

00:16:19.317 --> 00:16:20.650
I'm fine with four-letter words.

00:16:20.650 --> 00:16:23.210
I can just-- so, too
much pressure for whom?

00:16:23.210 --> 00:16:26.330
AUDIENCE: For us,
for [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:27.924 --> 00:16:28.840
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Oh.

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:32.030
AUDIENCE: Even though I think
we still tried to do that,

00:16:32.030 --> 00:16:33.490
it didn't feel--

00:16:33.490 --> 00:16:36.420
it felt, like, OK, what
are 10 important events you

00:16:36.420 --> 00:16:38.070
can come up with.

00:16:38.070 --> 00:16:39.820
AUDIENCE: And it's subjective.

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:42.630
What's most important
to me is probably not

00:16:42.630 --> 00:16:47.628
what's most important to you, or
her, or whoever's sitting here.

00:16:47.628 --> 00:16:49.002
STEPHEN CARPENTER: OK.

00:16:49.002 --> 00:16:51.520
AUDIENCE: "Most" might have
got in the way of the word

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:52.150
"important."

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:54.480
Because if you don't have
the "most" there, you think,

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:57.285
what is important,
and [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:57.285 --> 00:16:59.660
STEPHEN CARPENTER: So it's
kind of a pedagogical strategy

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:02.900
to take some stress
away, to allow entry,

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:05.869
to remove some of the
complications embedded

00:17:05.869 --> 00:17:08.339
in just working out the
different values ahead of time

00:17:08.339 --> 00:17:08.839
anyway.

00:17:08.839 --> 00:17:10.730
I mean, certainly, those
are important conversations.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:11.355
Not the stress.

00:17:11.355 --> 00:17:13.430
I don't like to induce
stress in students.

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:16.819
But to make an activity
or allow an activity

00:17:16.819 --> 00:17:19.460
to have points of
entry for people

00:17:19.460 --> 00:17:23.060
where they feel like they can
be part of that work is crucial.

00:17:23.060 --> 00:17:25.890
AUDIENCE: I also think that
now, that all the lists are

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:29.160
done, that because the
word "most" is not there,

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:30.670
it's not a final list.

00:17:30.670 --> 00:17:34.010
So I can look at
somebody else's list

00:17:34.010 --> 00:17:36.720
and say, OK, that is
also important, as

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:41.330
opposed to a final list
of the most important.

00:17:41.330 --> 00:17:45.621
So it allows for changing
after it's done up there.

00:17:45.621 --> 00:17:46.870
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Absolutely.

00:17:46.870 --> 00:17:48.130
So it's not fixed.

00:17:48.130 --> 00:17:49.570
Absolutely.

00:17:49.570 --> 00:17:51.840
But that notion of curriculum,
for a lot of people--

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:52.800
it's fixed.

00:17:52.800 --> 00:17:54.390
It's done.

00:17:54.390 --> 00:17:55.800
It's a noun.

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:56.640
It's not a running.

00:17:56.640 --> 00:17:57.660
It's not a continuation.

00:17:57.660 --> 00:17:59.550
It's not a springboard
and a prompt.

00:17:59.550 --> 00:18:01.350
You're exactly right.

00:18:01.350 --> 00:18:03.012
It's a point of
continuous learning.

00:18:03.012 --> 00:18:03.720
Yeah, good stuff.

00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:07.590
All right, so let's
slide back up here.

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:12.080
Wow, this is about 20 years ago.

00:18:12.080 --> 00:18:16.740
And I was working with
hypertext software, story space.

00:18:16.740 --> 00:18:18.940
So you kind of see that
map in the upper left.

00:18:18.940 --> 00:18:22.350
And my idea was, I go
to the barber shop,

00:18:22.350 --> 00:18:24.960
and I get my haircut.

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:27.880
But I learn a lot of
stuff in that barber shop.

00:18:27.880 --> 00:18:31.316
I think this barber shop
might be a curriculum.

00:18:31.316 --> 00:18:33.720
It might be an
educational space.

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:35.700
No, it's a hypertext.

00:18:35.700 --> 00:18:38.610
There's a bunch of moving parts
and different relation-- maybe

00:18:38.610 --> 00:18:39.945
it's all of those things.

00:18:39.945 --> 00:18:44.490
So I started to overlap those
different thoughts into a piece

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:46.290
called "Pat's Barbershop."

00:18:46.290 --> 00:18:48.900
One day I asked the gathering
of barbers and clients,

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.670
what can someone learn in here?

00:18:50.670 --> 00:18:52.890
Meaning, what can someone
learn in this barber shop?

00:18:52.890 --> 00:18:55.410
And this barber shop is
in Norfolk, Virginia,

00:18:55.410 --> 00:18:59.160
predominately African-American
segment of Norfolk.

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:03.510
This was when I was on faculty
at Old Dominion University.

00:19:03.510 --> 00:19:05.417
So I asked Pat, the
owner and lead barber,

00:19:05.417 --> 00:19:06.750
what can somebody learn in here?

00:19:06.750 --> 00:19:08.166
And according to
Pat, people learn

00:19:08.166 --> 00:19:10.020
a lot about life,
education, business,

00:19:10.020 --> 00:19:11.640
the street, the whole nine.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:16.560
Someone else noted with a smirk,
they learn what a gram is.

00:19:16.560 --> 00:19:20.700
He was talking about
illicit substances.

00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:23.460
How much you can get
for a stolen TV--

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.260
"and they can learn
that crack is good.

00:19:25.260 --> 00:19:27.330
We love crackheads."

00:19:27.330 --> 00:19:28.862
What he meant was--

00:19:28.862 --> 00:19:30.820
the first part he was
actually being sarcastic.

00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:36.420
But the second part, he
was being more supportive.

00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:39.450
In a matter-of-fact
tone, one of the barbers

00:19:39.450 --> 00:19:42.900
commented, If you could put
a camera in here for a week,

00:19:42.900 --> 00:19:44.790
you could make a movie.

00:19:44.790 --> 00:19:47.280
At one point, Pat himself
responded to my question

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:49.980
in a melodic chant, "OJ did it!

00:19:49.980 --> 00:19:53.280
OJ did it!--" a reference to a
scene in the movie Barbershop

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:55.230
and the famous court trial.

00:19:55.230 --> 00:19:57.480
Later, in a more serious
tone, Pat proudly

00:19:57.480 --> 00:20:01.200
stated, "Younger
teenagers, learn from me.

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:06.540
Don't sell drugs, be successful,
keep a straight head."

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:12.140
Pat admitted that, in his place,
you learn about everyday life.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:17.987
And this project
went on for years.

00:20:17.987 --> 00:20:19.320
And they'd call me "Professor"--

00:20:19.320 --> 00:20:20.534
"Hey, Professor, guess what?"

00:20:20.534 --> 00:20:22.950
And they would start to tell
me what they learned recently

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:24.100
until I'd get new lessons.

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:28.350
And so this article is
filled with different ways

00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:32.490
to think about that
barbershop as a hypertext.

00:20:32.490 --> 00:20:35.370
Looking at other
subsequent work, not only

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:38.190
am I artist in residence
here at MIT this year,

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:40.080
but I'm also an
artist in residence

00:20:40.080 --> 00:20:44.820
at a local elementary
school back where I live.

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:47.200
I've been working with first
graders and third graders.

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:48.825
So you know what I
did a few weeks ago?

00:20:48.825 --> 00:20:51.250
I talked to third graders
about epidemiology,

00:20:51.250 --> 00:20:53.092
which is what you do, right?

00:20:53.092 --> 00:20:55.274
I showed them this map.

00:20:55.274 --> 00:20:56.940
My intention wasn't
to talk specifically

00:20:56.940 --> 00:20:58.830
about epidemiology.

00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:00.750
My intention was
to talk about how

00:21:00.750 --> 00:21:03.800
the visual
representation of ideas

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:06.075
or how the visual
representation of data

00:21:06.075 --> 00:21:08.010
and the visual
representation of information

00:21:08.010 --> 00:21:11.940
might allow us access to ways
of knowing and understanding

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:15.540
that we wouldn't have without
those visual representations.

00:21:15.540 --> 00:21:18.360
So here, we have a
segment of London.

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:20.585
And you see a bunch
of dots there.

00:21:20.585 --> 00:21:23.220
And those dots,
essentially, are the places

00:21:23.220 --> 00:21:28.440
where John Snow,
in the late 1800s,

00:21:28.440 --> 00:21:32.260
identified people who
had died from cholera.

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:34.840
And his theory, which was
different than local theory

00:21:34.840 --> 00:21:38.390
and the common theory
at that point--

00:21:38.390 --> 00:21:41.140
his theory was, people were
getting cholera from water.

00:21:41.140 --> 00:21:42.280
Everybody else, said, no!

00:21:42.280 --> 00:21:43.840
It's in the air.

00:21:43.840 --> 00:21:45.190
Or, it's divine intervention.

00:21:45.190 --> 00:21:46.481
Or, something else is going on.

00:21:46.481 --> 00:21:48.980
John, you don't know what
you're talking about.

00:21:48.980 --> 00:21:51.964
So I told the kids this.

00:21:51.964 --> 00:21:53.130
I didn't tell them this yet.

00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:53.790
I said, here's a map.

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:54.550
What do you see?

00:21:54.550 --> 00:21:55.590
Oh, it's a map.

00:21:55.590 --> 00:21:56.109
OK.

00:21:56.109 --> 00:21:57.150
And what else do you see?

00:21:57.150 --> 00:21:58.110
Well, I see a bunch of dots.

00:21:58.110 --> 00:21:59.160
What do you think
those dots are?

00:21:59.160 --> 00:22:00.035
Those are the people.

00:22:00.035 --> 00:22:01.111
That's where they live.

00:22:01.111 --> 00:22:02.860
Or, maybe that's where
something happened.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:03.930
Why are there more dots
here and not over there?

00:22:03.930 --> 00:22:04.430
I don't know.

00:22:04.430 --> 00:22:06.120
And they said, oh,
wait, there's some X's.

00:22:06.120 --> 00:22:07.020
What do you think those X's are?

00:22:07.020 --> 00:22:07.920
And they had all these ideas.

00:22:07.920 --> 00:22:08.730
Well, you don't see the X's?

00:22:08.730 --> 00:22:09.630
Here are the X's.

00:22:09.630 --> 00:22:10.972
The X's are here.

00:22:10.972 --> 00:22:11.930
Oh, OK, that's helpful.

00:22:11.930 --> 00:22:13.330
Thanks.

00:22:13.330 --> 00:22:14.210
So what's going on?

00:22:14.210 --> 00:22:16.710
Tell me about the relationship
between the X's and the dots.

00:22:16.710 --> 00:22:19.300
Oh, well, most of the dots are
in the middle, and most of them

00:22:19.300 --> 00:22:20.860
are on that green
dot in the center.

00:22:20.860 --> 00:22:22.250
I said, oh, you know what?

00:22:22.250 --> 00:22:24.040
That's what John
Snow thought, too.

00:22:24.040 --> 00:22:25.480
Guess what he figured out?

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:27.940
That's where the people
were getting sick.

00:22:27.940 --> 00:22:29.940
That's where the people
were dying, because they

00:22:29.940 --> 00:22:31.270
were drinking the water.

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:34.530
And it was because he was able
to visually represent the data,

00:22:34.530 --> 00:22:39.474
he could get to
this observation.

00:22:39.474 --> 00:22:40.890
They thought that
was pretty cool.

00:22:40.890 --> 00:22:43.740
Then, I told them,
so now, here's

00:22:43.740 --> 00:22:47.952
a new word-- epidemiology.

00:22:47.952 --> 00:22:49.410
A bunch of eight
and nine-year-olds

00:22:49.410 --> 00:22:50.370
saying, "epidemiology."

00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:52.790
It was great.

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:57.590
But they start to understand
how visual representation

00:22:57.590 --> 00:23:00.650
of information allows access
to ideas in different ways.

00:23:00.650 --> 00:23:03.700
And I said, if you like this
map, what about this one?

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:06.115
Other people thought that
that map was interesting, too.

00:23:06.115 --> 00:23:07.490
How many different
ways could you

00:23:07.490 --> 00:23:11.090
represent data
visually using a map?

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:13.910
Other people thought John
Snow's idea was really cool.

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:15.860
Oh, and then as soon
as I showed this, oh!

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:18.550
That's Google Maps!

00:23:18.550 --> 00:23:21.250
Eight and nine-year-olds
know about Google Maps?

00:23:21.250 --> 00:23:22.683
Yeah.

00:23:22.683 --> 00:23:23.650
Hmm.

00:23:23.650 --> 00:23:25.450
So now, how does
Google Maps play

00:23:25.450 --> 00:23:29.140
into how we might teach
in elementary school

00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:33.030
about space, about
visual representation?

00:23:33.030 --> 00:23:35.160
Just taking an object,
and doing something to it,

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:38.110
and doing something else to it?

00:23:38.110 --> 00:23:42.000
I do something similar with
my preservice teachers.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:43.680
As they're preparing
to become teachers

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:46.254
and preparing to go out into
classrooms to do their student

00:23:46.254 --> 00:23:47.670
teaching, when
they're just trying

00:23:47.670 --> 00:23:49.770
to figure out how
learning and teaching

00:23:49.770 --> 00:23:51.300
happens in educational
spaces, one

