I know from teaching drawing,
one technique we can do,

00:35:24.742 --> 00:35:26.450
if we put a chair, or
a series of chairs,

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:28.290
or still life in the
middle of the room,

00:35:28.290 --> 00:35:30.502
we all had our drawing paper.

00:35:30.502 --> 00:35:31.960
We could start
drawing what we see.

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:33.860
And that would get us so far.

00:35:33.860 --> 00:35:37.180
But one strategy an art teacher
will always do or often do

00:35:37.180 --> 00:35:39.400
is say, I want you to
draw what's not there.

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:41.290
I want you to draw
the negative space.

00:35:41.290 --> 00:35:44.500
And when you draw the negative
spaces between the chair,

00:35:44.500 --> 00:35:47.200
the spaces between the bars, and
the spaces between the handles

00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:48.190
and the rungs--

00:35:48.190 --> 00:35:50.380
by drawing and rendering
those negative spaces

00:35:50.380 --> 00:35:55.120
as accurately as possible, you
render the positive spaces.

00:35:55.120 --> 00:35:57.280
So what do we learn by
studying what is not

00:35:57.280 --> 00:35:58.750
there or the neglected spaces?

00:35:58.750 --> 00:36:04.010
We learn more about the presence
of the dominant structure.

00:36:04.010 --> 00:36:06.110
So there are a number
of books about pedagogy

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:10.850
and about translating art
practice and pedagogical

00:36:10.850 --> 00:36:14.400
engagements in
public spaces, right?

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:17.310
So I'll just conclude
here for some questions.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:22.602
You know, you can engage
learners like this--

00:36:22.602 --> 00:36:23.810
or you could do boring stuff.

00:36:23.810 --> 00:36:25.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:25.890
It's up to you.

00:36:25.890 --> 00:36:27.120
All right, thanks.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:31.970
